  caseStudyTitle="Why chlorine alone isn't enough under Encino's tree canopy"
  caseStudy="Encino's mature, heavily landscaped properties are part of what makes the neighborhood beautiful, and part of what keeps us busy. Large trees mean a steady drop of organic matter into the water, and organic matter breaks down into phosphates that feed algae even when chlorine levels look fine on paper. For Encino pools under heavy tree cover, we typically add phosphate remover to the regular chemical rotation and clean filters more frequently than we would on a more open property. It's a small adjustment, but skipping it is one of the most common reasons a well-chlorinated pool still turns green by late summer. We factor this into scheduling from the first visit rather than waiting for a client to notice a problem."
